48
05:03.270 --> 05:11.640
The general description, on
the other hand, is more general and ultimately, it's more
powerful in a mathematical sense.

49
05:11.640 --> 05:18.720
In this description, quantum states are represented by a special class of matrices
called density matrices,

50
05:18.720 --> 05:25.830
and more general class of
measurements and operations can be described including
noise, for instance.

51
05:25.830 --> 05:32.280
It's entirely consistent with
the simplified description and in fact, you can essentially view
the simplified description

52
05:32.280 --> 05:39.330
as a special case of
the general description, and it also includes classical information as a special case.

53
05:39.330 --> 05:46.020
It's also really quite
beautiful in how it all works, so I strongly encourage you to learn about this general description

54
05:46.020 --> 05:53.220
when the time is right, but the simplified description is the more natural place to start, and so that is what we will do.

55
05:53.220 --> 06:01.770
We're going to begin by talking about classical information with an eye on the aspects
of classical information that are most relevant
to quantum information

56
06:01.770 --> 06:06.060
and the way that it's
described mathematically.

57
06:06.060 --> 06:12.330
Imagine that we have a
physical system or a device of some sort that stores information.

58
06:12.330 --> 06:16.800
We're gonna give this system the name X, but there's nothing
important about this name.

59
06:16.800 --> 06:24.180
We could use any other
name if we preferred, but just to pick a name,
we're gonna call the system X.

60
06:24.180 --> 06:33.120
We're gonna make an assumption about X, which is that there is a
finite set of classical states that X can possibly be
in at any given moment.

61
06:33.120 --> 06:41.100
Here, when I refer to a classical state, I mean a configuration of the system that can be recognized and
described unambiguously

62
06:41.100 --> 06:44.520
without any uncertainty or error.

63
06:44.520 --> 06:51.420
Really, this is something that you can think about intuitively. At a mathematical level, we simply define the
set of classical states,

64
06:51.420 --> 06:58.560
we choose it however we want to or in whatever way best
describes the device that we're working with.

65
06:58.560 --> 07:07.050
Let us give the name sigma to
this set of classical states, and again, let me emphasize
that we're assuming that sigma is a finite set.

66
07:07.050 --> 07:12.570
The set of classical
states of this system X is not infinitely large like
the set of all natural numbers.

67
07:12.570 --> 07:17.850
It's finite, and that's just an
assumption that we're making.

68
07:17.850 --> 07:27.540
For example, it could be that X is a bit, in which case, the classical state set is the set containing two
elements: zero and one.

69
07:27.540 --> 07:32.070
Sometimes we refer to this
set as the binary alphabet.

70
07:32.070 --> 07:40.470
Another example is that X is
an ordinary six-sided die, in which case, the classical states are the numbers one through six.

71
07:40.470 --> 07:43.500
Of course, we're talking
about an abstraction here.

72
07:43.500 --> 07:50.040
An actual six-sided die may
have many different attributes such as its precise
position, its orientation,

73
07:50.040 --> 07:58.200
its temperature, and so on. But with respect to the information that's most typically relevant when we're talking about a six-sided die,

74
07:58.200 --> 08:07.140
the classical states are
the numbers one through six indicated by the number of dots on whichever side of the die is facing up.

75
08:07.140 --> 08:14.250
If X is a switch on a
standard sort of electric fan that you might have in your home, then perhaps the classical states

76
08:14.250 --> 08:18.900
are the settings high,
medium, low and off.

77
08:18.900 --> 08:25.830
These are just examples. We could imagine systems having different classical
state sets than these, but hopefully, they convey the idea

78
08:25.830 --> 08:34.620
that this notion of a classical state is something that should be
familiar and can be understood in simple and intuitive terms.

79
08:34.620 --> 08:41.190
Mathematically speaking, the set of classical states
is just a finite set, and of course, this set must
also be non empty as well.

80
08:41.190 --> 08:47.490
There has to be at least
one classical state that the system can be in and there has to be at
least two classical states

81
08:47.490 --> 08:53.190
if the system is going to be useful at all for storing information.

82
08:53.190 --> 08:59.610
Now, in some situations, we might know that X is
in some particular state, but in many situations,

83
08:59.610 --> 09:07.140
that arise in the setting
of information processing, there may be uncertainty about the classical state of a
system at a particular moment

84
09:07.140 --> 09:12.600
so that each possible classical state has some probability associated with it.

85
09:12.600 --> 09:19.140
For example, if X is a bit, then perhaps it's the case that X is in the classical state zero

86
09:19.140 --> 09:25.830
with probability three quarters and it's in the state one
with probability one quarter.

87
09:25.830 --> 09:32.580
We're going to refer to this
as a probabilistic state, and we could express
this probabilistic state, as you see right here,

88
09:32.580 --> 09:38.580
simply by indicating what
the probabilities are for the different classical states.

89
09:38.580 --> 09:47.910
A more succinct way to express
this probabilistic state is by a vector, specifically the representation
that you see right here

90
09:47.910 --> 09:55.380
is a column vector, and this vector indicates
what the probabilities are for the two possible classical states.

91
09:55.380 --> 10:03.960
To be more specific, the first entry indicates
what the probability is for X to be in the state zero, and the second entry tells
us what the probability is

92
10:03.960 --> 10:10.350
for the system to be in the state one. This is simply the natural way to order the binary alphabet,

93
10:10.350 --> 10:16.890
or at least, it's the way that
we are trained to do this. With zero first and one second.

94
10:16.890 --> 10:22.500
Going forward, we're gonna use
the term probability vector to indicate a vector like this.

